      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":1,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":7,\"target_duration_minutes\":43,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":370,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":370,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start very easy, let your body wake up. Focus on relaxed breathing and loose shoulders.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":33,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":370,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Maintain conversational pace throughout. You should be able to speak in full sentences. Heart rate should stay well below threshold.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Gradually slow to a walk in the final minute. Follow with light hip flexor and IT band stretches given your history.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Begin with 5 minutes of brisk walking or very easy jogging before settling into your easy pace.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 2-3 minutes after finishing. Prioritize IT band stretches (standing cross-leg stretch, foam roll lateral thigh) given your history.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This is your foundational aerobic run for the week. Easy runs build your aerobic base, improve fat oxidation, and aid recovery from harder efforts. Resist the urge to push — the purpose is aerobic stimulus at low stress. Your easy pace range is 5:50–6:27/km; aim for the middle of that range today around 6:10/km.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"title\":\"Threshold Cruise Intervals\",\"target_distance_km\":10,\"target_duration_minutes\":55,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":370,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":290,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":12,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy jog for 2km (~12 min). Include 4x20-second strides in the final 2 minutes to prime your legs for threshold effort.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":290,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"First cruise interval at 4:50/km. This should feel comfortably hard — you can speak a few words but not full sentences. Controlled and steady.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":2,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy jog recovery between intervals. Keep moving, don't stop completely.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":290,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Second cruise interval at 4:50/km. Maintain the same controlled effort as the first. Focus on smooth, efficient form.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":2,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy jog recovery. Shake out your legs and reset your breathing before the final interval.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":290,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Third cruise interval at 4:50/km. Slightly shorter — push through to the end with good form. Don't let pace slip in the final minutes.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":11,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy 2km jog to flush lactate. Gradual deceleration. Follow with dynamic stretching.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"2km easy jog (~12 min) followed by 4 short strides (20 sec each at slightly faster than threshold pace with full recovery between). This primes your neuromuscular system for the work ahead.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"2km easy jog (~11 min). Do not skip this — it accelerates lactate clearance. Follow with calf raises, hip flexor stretches, and IT band work.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Cruise intervals are the cornerstone of half marathon preparation. Running at threshold pace (4:50/km) raises your lactate threshold, which directly determines your sustainable race pace. Three intervals with short recoveries simulate sustained threshold stress while allowing slightly more total volume than a continuous tempo run. This is a step up from your recent 4km tempo work — the progression is intentional and appropriate for your current fitness.\",\"perceived_effort\":7},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"workout_type\":\"Recovery\",\"title\":\"Active Recovery Run\",\"target_distance_km\":6,\"target_duration_minutes\":39,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":387,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":387,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":39,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Run at the very easy end of your easy range (6:27/km or slower). This is purely recovery — no pace pressure whatsoever. Focus on relaxed form and breathing.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"No formal warmup needed — the entire run IS the warmup pace. Start with 2 minutes of walking if legs feel heavy from yesterday's tempo.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 3-5 minutes. Spend 10 minutes on mobility: IT band stretches, hip circles, calf stretches. Consider a light foam roll session.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"The day after a threshold session, your body needs blood flow and movement without additional stress. This recovery run flushes metabolic waste, reduces muscle soreness, and keeps your aerobic system ticking without digging into recovery reserves. Keep it genuinely easy — if in doubt, slow down. Your IT band history makes this day especially important; don't skip the mobility work.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":5,\"workout_type\":\"Interval\",\"title\":\"VO2Max Intervals\",\"target_distance_km\":9,\"target_duration_minutes\":52,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":370,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":271,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":12,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"2km easy jog. Include 4-6 strides (20-25 sec each at interval pace effort) with full walking recovery. This is critical preparation for hard interval work.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":4,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":271,\"intensity\":\"VO2Max\",\"repetitions\":5,\"notes\":\"5x 4-minute intervals at 4:31/km (interval pace). Each rep should feel very hard but controlled — not a sprint. Aim for even splits across all 5 reps. If you can't hold pace by rep 4-5, slow slightly rather than blowing up.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":4,\"notes\":\"3-minute easy jog recovery between each interval. Keep moving. Your breathing should recover significantly before the next rep begins.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":12,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"2km easy jog cooldown. Very gradual deceleration. Do not stop abruptly after hard intervals.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"2km easy jog (12 min) with 4-6 strides at near-interval effort. The strides are non-negotiable for interval sessions — they prepare your cardiovascular system and neuromuscular pathways for the hard work ahead.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"2km easy jog (12 min). Follow with full-body stretching focusing on quads, hamstrings, calves, and IT band. Hydrate and refuel within 30 minutes.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"VO2max intervals are the most physiologically demanding sessions in your plan. Running at 4:31/km maximally stresses your aerobic ceiling, forcing adaptations that raise your VO2max over time. For half marathon performance, a higher VO2max gives you more headroom above your threshold. Five 4-minute reps is a classic, well-researched prescription. The key is consistency across reps — a controlled hard effort, not an all-out sprint. This is your hardest workout of the week; protect the days around it.\",\"perceived_effort\":9},{\"day_of_week\":0,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Long Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":16,\"target_duration_minutes\":104,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":387,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":370,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":400,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"First 10 minutes very easy — slower than your easy pace. Let your body fully warm up before settling into your long run rhythm.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":74,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Steady aerobic effort at 6:27/km. This should feel genuinely comfortable — you're building time on feet, not chasing pace. Focus on relaxed form, especially in the second half when fatigue sets in.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":370,\"intensity\":\"Moderate\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Optional: final 10 minutes at the faster end of easy pace (5:50-6:00/km) if you feel strong. This teaches your body to run efficiently when fatigued. Skip this if you're struggling — the distance is the priority today.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":400,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Final 10 minutes very easy, transitioning to a walk in the last 2 minutes. Do not stop abruptly.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Start slower than you think you need to. The first 10-15 minutes of a long run should feel almost too easy. Resist the urge to settle into pace too quickly.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 5 minutes after finishing. Prioritize post-run nutrition within 30-45 minutes. Spend 15 minutes on stretching: IT band, hip flexors, calves, hamstrings. Consider an ice pack on the lateral knee if any tightness is felt.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"The long run is the most important workout of your week for half marathon preparation. At 16km, this is a meaningful step up from your recent 14km long run — appropriate given the 10% weekly volume increase guideline. The goal is aerobic development and muscular endurance, not speed. Running at 6:27/km (the easy end of your range) ensures you're training the right energy systems. The optional final pickup teaches your body to maintain form under fatigue, which is directly relevant to the back half of your half marathon. Given your IT band history, pay close attention to any lateral knee discomfort and back off immediately if it arises.\",\"perceived_effort\":6}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
  "modelId": "\"claude-sonnet-4-6\"",
